SUMMARY

European Financial Centers as Strategic Nodes in the Financial Industry: London, Luxembourg and Vienna

by Sabine Dorry, Robert Musil

Hardly any other economic sector is as digitalized and globally integrated as the financial sector; it stands symptomatically for "globa­
lization” - including its negative side effects. The financial industry's expansion and "new quality", at the latest since the 1980s, is inse­
parably linked with the historical transformation of old financial centers as well as the rise of new ones. Financial centers are important 
nodes within a global network of flows of information and capital, in which financial products are developed, assets are administered 
and securities are traded. They are therefore engines of a global development as much as they are impacted by these global develop­
ments and prone to increasing competition. This paper illuminates the substantial spatial and functional differences of the European 
financial centers by exemplifying the three case studies London, Luxembourg and Vienna. We discuss the interdependency between 
national regulations and historical trajectories of each of the centers. We consider this a decisive factor for the development of manifold 
and highly specialized European financial centers, which have been coping differently with the impacts of the financial crisis.

